text: Today, we honor the pioneers of the labor movement, men and women who put their lives on the line, demanding fair labor practices for the workers who helped to build this country. Because of their sacrifices, we have healthcare, pensions, vacations, and fair working hours. The labor movement is responsible for workplace safety, helps protect children from being exploited in the workplace, and is responsible for building the middle class in America. We must never forget that organized labor continues its struggle for justice, fairness, and the constant fight to increase the minimum wage, especially at the federal level.

John Lewis was truly a human being who dedicated his life and career to the struggle for civil rights, human rights, and equality for all in this country. During the march for voting rights, John Lewis was viciously beaten and almost lost his life at the foot of the Edmund Pettus Bridge
in Selma, Alabama. Each year, many members of Congress and I make the trip to Selma and walk across the Edmund Pettus Bridge in honor of John Lewis and the brave men and women who sacrificed for civil rights alongside Martin Luther King Jr. John Lewis will forever be memorialized in history for his tremendous contributions. I am proud that John and I were great friends. We worked together in the Civil Rights movement and the Congress of the United States of America. I will never forget his awesome sacrifice to uplift our people and make America a better place for everyone.

Jewel Thais-Williams was an extraordinary human being. She was the most dedicated advocate for the LGBTQ community, and she created the fabulous nightclub, Jewel’s Catch One Disco. Catch One became a welcoming spot for the LGBTQ community and for many Hollywood stars and entertainers. It became a safe haven for those who were not wanted in many places in our community. Not only did she provide a very hip and well-attended nightclub, but she also worked and created funding and resources to deal with HIV/AIDS when our country was in denial. In addition to supporting healthcare for the LGBTQ community, she also became an acupuncturist. She was a dear friend, and I enjoyed all the times we worked together. She will definitely be remembered and missed!

The President must be confronted by Members of Congress to be reminded that the President must come before Congress to seek approval before a declaration of war. This action by the President is typical of a president out of control. The United States at one time had an agreement with Iran, and that agreement was monitored closely. But Trump withdrew from that agreement when he took office. Trump is out of control and does not contribute to an establishment of peace. June 19th is a special day, celebrated by so many families, churches, friends, and institutions who are focused on this national holiday because of what it means in our lives. We celebrate Juneteenth because in 1865, two years after the Emancipation Proclamation, word got to Texas that the slaves had been freed. It is important that we continue the struggle for total freedom, justice, and equality. We must never forget that journey that brought us to America.

On June 12th, 1963, one of our country’s greatest Civil Rights leaders, Medgar Evers, was assassinated in Jackson, Mississippi. Medgar was the NAACP’s first Field Secretary for Mississippi and was a tireless worker and promoter of voting rights. Medgar's death sent a shockwave through the African American community and triggered increased marches and protests against racism, segregation, and discrimination. Medgar's wife, Myrlie Evers, a civil rights leader in her own right, became a chair of the national NAACP after his death. My sincere condolences to the entire Medgar Evers family. May he rest in peace.

All people deserve to be treated with dignity and due process under the law. Peaceful, nonviolent demonstrations are critical to protecting our constitutional rights!

Today, as I memorialize the loss of so many of our men and women who paid the ultimate sacrifice for serving our nation, I am also mourning the loss of my dear friend and colleague, Congressman Charlie Rangel. Congressman Rangel has passed, but he left a legacy of service and commitment to this country for us all to try to emulate. Congressman Rangel excelled in his service in the United States Army, he was a dedicated veteran who was awarded the Purple Heart and the Bronze Star with valor. He was a co-founder of the Congressional Black Caucus. He was a prolific legislator who fought not only for civil rights but for veterans, healthcare, education, and organized labor. I worked closely with Congressman Rangel as we worked to eliminate apartheid in South Africa. He left a record of leadership to be recorded in history. My friend retired in 2017, and I’ve missed him every day since then. I will honor him & his legacy of service by supporting all of the causes that he led in the US House of Representatives. Farewell, my dear friend. God bless you and all the loved ones you leave behind.

35 years ago one of the world’s greatest leaders was released from prison. Nelson Mandela led the struggle against apartheid in South Africa and was jailed and served 27 years in prison.
 
I joined the struggle against apartheid by introducing legislation in the California State Assembly to divest all of our pension funds from businesses doing business in South Africa.
 
Mandela became president of South Africa and freed South Africans from the worst racism, discrimination, poverty, and dominance the world has ever known.

This is the beginning of Black History Month, and while I believe we should celebrate Black History every day, it is so important to understand everything that we have fought for, the sacrifices that have been made, the lives that have been lost, the bondage and slavery that our people have survived, it is all at stake now. Trump has attacked diversity and inclusion. He has attacked legal funding for programs and projects all over this country, in urban and rural communities, funding that we have fought for everyone. This Black History Month, we cannot go back. We must go forward. Everyone must understand we are in this struggle for as long as it takes. The fight is on!

Today, I am concentrating on everything that I and our governments can do to stop the fires that are devastating our communities of the Pacific Palisades of West Los Angeles, Malibu, the Eaton Fire north of Pasadena, and the Hurst Fire in the San Fernando Valley, as well as other areas that may also be affected such as Santa Monica. These fires have already reaped tremendous devastation on the homes and families of these areas, and I am praying that our frontline firefighters will be able to contain these fires as soon as possible. Already, 80,000 people or more have been evacuated, and even more families may have to be evacuated. Despite the horror and devastation of these fires, I encourage the families to obey the instructions of all of our frontline workers and do whatever is necessary to save lives. President Biden has assured members of Congress that the White House is doing anything and everything possible, and we have already started the discussion about the financial devastation that has taken place and what will be the tremendous need for appropriations to deal with the recovery. I strongly support a bipartisan, bicameral effort to do everything possible to give real assistance to all of the neighborhoods of Los Angeles County and beyond if necessary. For further information, please call 800-927-4357.

Jimmy Carter, the 39th President of the United States, was a courageous President who made Human Rights a priority in his presidency. He worked around the world for peace, and he understood his presidency was not only responsible for a strong domestic agenda but also should be a leader in international relations. He was, indeed, a man of faith who, even up until recently, taught Sunday School even when he was fighting cancer. He will be remembered not only for his presidency but also for his work with Habitat for Humanity, where, for many years after his presidency, he and his wife, Rosalynn, built housing for the poor. His dedication to “the least of them” will be favorably recorded in history!

Quincy Jones, a musical genius and the producer of Michael Jackson's "Thriller," the best-selling album of all time, has passed. He was unmatched in the creativity of his many productions. I will never forget how he worked with me to present Nelson Mandela, where 90 thousand people showed up at the Los Angeles Coliseum following his release from prison in South Africa. Quincy Jones will never be forgotten! Rest in peace, my dear friend.

In honor of National Breast Cancer Awareness Month, I introduced two bills to support cancer patients. H.R. 10058 requires states to provide both cancer treatment and inform the recipients they are eligible for reconstruction after mastectomy! H.R. 10060 requires doctors who perform mastectomies for Medicare patients to tell them that Medicare covers breast reconstruction!
